==The Russian word '''soviet''' [[совет]]==

'''Soviet''' [[совет]], is a [[Russian]] [[abstract noun]] meaning '[[advice]]', '[[counsel]]', or '[[council]]'. In the past 200 years, and especially the past 100, it has also taken on some more [[concrete noun|concrete]] meanings.

===Pronunciation===

The [[vowel]] of the first syllable is pronounced similarly to the [[letter (alphabet)|letter]] 'u' in the [[English language|English]] [[word]] 'sud', and the [[stress (linguistics)|stress]] is always on the second [[syllable]].

===Usage===

The word mainly denotes one of five meanings:

* a '''piece of advice''', or '''advice or counsel in general'''. (In this meaning, it is always an abstract noun, and does not denote 'a counsel' meaning a type of legal practitioner).

* a '''group [[meeting]] of practically any kind''', especially one held (whether regularly or in extraordinary circumstances) in order '''to reach a [[collective]] [[decision]]''', e.g. a family meeting is known a family soviet [[семейный совет]], 

* a high-level '''State council''' of any kind, e.g.
**the [[State]] Soviet [[Государственный совет]], established by [[Alexander I of Russia|Tsar Alexander I]], who reigned from 1801 to 1825
**a '''privy council'''
**the currently-existing Security Councils of the [[Security Council|United Nations]], the [[National Security Council|United States]] or the [[Security Council of the Russian Federation|Russian Federation]].

* a '''[[workers' councils|soviet (workers' council)]]''', whether:
**one of the '''workers' bodies''' formed in 1905 or 1917 in Russia, or at other times in other countries, being a body of delegates representing, or chosen to further the achievement of the goals of, workers from several workplaces who are engaged in organised combative struggle; or
** one of the '''governmental bodies''' (local, regional, and central [[council|councils]]) which in [[icon|iconic]] terms claimed a legacy from the workers' councils of 1917, and in theory controlled the executive organs of government (the highest such body being the [[Supreme Soviet]]).

*one of '''various State bodies in Russia today''', including [[local government|local councils]] which have organisationally succeeded bodies that existed prior to [[1991]], but which no longer claim a legacy related to workers' organisations


The [[adjective]] 'sovetskii' [[советский]], formed from the noun, is mainly used to denote the former [[country]] known as the [[Soviet Union]], with reference to its system of [[government]], the [[ideology]] thereof, and the [[political culture]]

==Use as a loanword in other languages==

The word 'soviet' has been adopted as a [[loanword]] into other [[language|languages]], including [[English language|English]].

In [[English language|English]], the main uses have been:

*in the fourth set of meanings above

*in the meanings denoted in Russian by the [[adjective]].

